segments.text: First, Mr. Hill, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places of their birth and death, where they were born, where you were born, I mean, and the date of your birth, and the schools you attended before you came to Texas A&M.
Well, my father's name was Fielding Hill, and my mother's name was Minta, M-I-N-T-A.
Both of my parents died in Dallas in the Terrell, T-E-R-R-I-L-L, nursing home.
My father was 88 years, 12 months, and nine days.
I mean, nine months and 12 days.
And my mother was 93 years and one week.
Why not tell him where you were born?
And I was born at...
at Wills Point, Texas, which is 50 miles.
Well, it's known as Wills Point.
Do you remember where your parents were born?
Yes, my mother was born in Mississippi.
My father was born where?
Oh, no.
Where was he born?
Oh, baby.
What are you telling them?
I don't remember.
I'm sure my father was born in I think Alabama.
Alabama.
And I know my mother was born in Mississippi.
Did you go to school in Wills Point?
Yes, I finished high school in Wills Point.
You went as many grades as they had there.
Yes, 12.
12 grades.
In 1917, about the first of June, of course, and then that fall I went to A&M.
What type of business was your father in?
We farmed about 400 acres with hired labor, which was rather unusual at that time.
and then he was in the cotton seed and grain business.

Planting seed, he, we, well that's what I spent my time as a young boy from the time I was eight years old on taking care of the farm with like cotton choppers and the pickers and I never could pick cotton but I could haul the cotton
to the gin and the way and things like that.
But I just, I just, my hands, I could get it in my hand, but I couldn't get it in my sack.
And so he said, son, you just don't know how to pick cotton.
You don't have to pick cotton.
But you were kind of a supervisor.
Right.
I was a supervisor.
And he, uh, we, it became necessary later on that we, you know, the, so many, uh,
of states wouldn't let our cottonseed come in like Arkansas wouldn't let them come in on account of the bow weevil.
So we made a drum type machine where the cottonseed went in and spilled over and went through a heat process of certain degrees.
And it was state approved and also approved by the other states like
We couldn't go into Oklahoma, we couldn't go into Louisiana, and we couldn't go into Arkansas.
But Arkansas was our main source.
That's where we sold most of the cotton seed.
And like we'd give $60 a ton for the seed, then we'd treat them and sack them.
And they were selected, of course.
And while this process was going on, all the little seed would drop out.
It would just save them.
what you call culling it, culling it and heeding it and killing the wheels.
So you bought the seed then from the farmer.
Your father bought the seed.
Yes, we kept our own seed.
We raised quite a few.
But then we would sell to a farmer, and then we would buy from him that fall.
Buy the seed back.
So you kept the same variety.
Right.
Rowden was it.
R-O-W-D-E-N was the name of the seed.
You mixed varieties in.
No, it was just the mebane and half and half and rowding were the three signs.
And the mebane and the other one were short staple.
The rowding was a long staple cotton.
They got up to $0.04 to $0.05 premium on the long staple.
Most of the other was 15, 16, which we'd get out here, and we would go one and an eighth and stuff like that with the rowding.
And so then you would process the seed and sell it wherever there was a market for it.
Yes.
My father would leave, and he'd probably get come back.
He'd be gone a week and come back with orders for maybe six or seven core load, which a core load is considered 1,000 bushels or 1,050 bushels.
And then you also, did you raise grain on your farm too?
Oh, yes.
What kind of grain?
Wheat.
Wheat.
Yes.
Wheat and oats.
And just oats to feed our stock, that was a prominent feed.
Okay, what factors influenced you to choose Texas A&M?
Well, of course, I had an older brother, Perch Hill, you know, and the other one, the three of the boys.
In fact, the four of them, four boys, all went to A&M.
So you were influenced by your older brother.
Yeah, and another thing that influenced me was
Leon Gilmore, which was later my brother-in-law, was a center on the 1917 team.
You know, 270 points to opponents, nothing.
And of course, I had room with him.
And Jack Finney, another boy from Willis Point who became a architect and taught at A&M for quite some years.
They were the men, too, that I wanted to be with.
OK.
What procedures did you go through to enter school?
Did you have to send your grades in advance, or did you just carry your transcript or record?
No, we sent them in advance.
And did you get a letter then from the school saying you were accepted?
Well, I really don't know that or whether Leon, my brother-in-law, handled it or
I know what we did, we'd take money, a check with us, to pay our tuition as we entered.
So you paid the tuition for what, one semester?
No, no, no.
The whole year?
The whole year.
And what was your first reaction?
Of course, having had a brother there, you were somewhat familiar to the school.
Well, it was rather unusual.
We got in there in the morning about, oh, 2.30.
And at that time, we were assigned to Miller, down the basement, right on the side next to where the old dining hall used to be.
I don't think it's there now, is it?
Well, Sbisa.
Yeah, Sbisa's still there.
I don't believe that is one, no, that's ten.
Anyhow.
At the end of Military Walk?
Yeah.
Yeah, that's Spesa.
Yeah.
Because the old mess hall burned in 13, I believe, and Spesa was constructed the following year, so.
Well, we were right near it, and to go in a strange place like that with no lights and sleep on just a mattress with no pillow,
It's not a very comfortable start, I'll say that.
No, I wouldn't think so.
You say you were saying, was there somebody there to meet the train and tell you where to go then?
Well, see, I was with Leon.
That was his sophomore year.
Okay, he was a sophomore.
And Jack and I were freshmen.
So he kind of took you in hand.
He took me in hand in Dallas and all, everything.
We had to go to Dallas and wait on the train.
We went shopping, bought shoes, and went, bought supplies that we'd need.
Then did you register to the day after you got there then?
I really don't know whether it'd be the next day or, I would think the next day.
Sometime fairly soon anyway.
I think the next day.
Did you have any choice about military company to which you were assigned?
Oh, no.
You were assigned.
Which one did you enter?
Company H, and I had a,
Coxy Evans was our captain from Fort Worth, which one of the, he was killed in the service.
Well, I think one of the finest men I ever knew in my life.
He was a leader and a fine man.
Where was Company H housed then?
In Millner.
So you spent the first night in Millner.
Did you stay in the basement after you were registered, or did you have a room elsewhere?
No, no.
I think we got that same room.
See, since my brother-in-law had been there a year, he knew the ropes, and I think he'd had the room the year before.
And then you roomed with him even though he was a sophomore.
Right.
Yeah, you could room with seniors or anyone at two.
that if he wanted for a roommate, you could arrange it.
I see.
Were you sort of his man then?
Did you do some chores for him from time to time?
No, he was pretty busy with his studies and football and everything, and I didn't see too much of him except at night.
But on Saturday night, the hazing was real bad at A&M at that time.
In fact, it was a little bit too bad.
Here it is, E.B.
Your mother was burned in Alabama but was reared on a plantation in northern Mississippi.
Melna Rutledge came to Texas with her family in 1883.
Did you stay in Milner all four years?
No, I didn't finish.
You didn't finish?
No.
I left the next October.
I was there the first year and then left...
See, my brother died.
You were there for 17, 18.
Yeah, yes.
And then went back.
And then my father, we were quarantined.
And my father wired me, come home immediately.
And we had all had the flu.
In fact, for three weeks, seven boys a day died in A&M.
And I was in Leggett at that time in an inner court there, you know, the courtyard.
There's three freshmen right across from me and all died and never had one dose of medicine or a doctor ever saw them.
And I had to lie there on my bed.
I couldn't get out.
And I had to lie and listen to those boys scream and died right there.
So the second year you went back, and that's when you had the flu epidemic in the 1819s.
Right.
That's during the war.
That's when everybody was in the SATC.
Yes.
But see, I was young enough.
I didn't have to join.
You didn't join the SATC.
No, no.
You went to regular classes in the second year?
Yeah, but I took the military training and everything.
In fact, I didn't have to do anything that I didn't want to do in the military.
Your daddy was born in Texas.
I knew he was.
This is that right up on there, 60th.
I thought he was a native Texan.
Yeah, I'm sorry.
He was in...
Panola County, that's down out of Carthage, between Carthage and the Shreveport line.
And they owned all that property down there, and he didn't want it.
He sold it, and that's where all the gas wells, oh, they're the...
But he did good.
He made us a good living.
This, talking about history, that is real interesting.
That tells about the marriage of his mother and father.
This was a...
60th wedding anniversary party we had for them years ago.
They were too ill to have their party at the 50th.
We had to wait until we were married 60 to have them.
Let me ask you, you left the school then in October of 18.
Yes.
Did you ever return then?
No.
No.
Okay.
What had you planned as your major?
What had you planned to study when you came to A&M?
Oh, I wanted to be a veterinary surgeon.
And since you... Did you ultimately become a veterinary surgeon then?
Only in practice.
I was in the contractor business.
I owned 60 head of mules.
Mm-hmm.
OK, skipping back, you mentioned when you arrived there, you were first assigned to Milner.
And then the second year, the part that you were there, you stayed in Leggett for a while.
The second year.
The second year, you were in Leggett for a couple months.
Right, in a room with a boat.
a boy by the name of Malcolm Broadfoot from Longview, Texas.
And he mixed all the syrups for Casey at the Y.
And when this flu epidemic came on, he had a key so he could make, he became ill first.
So he gave me the key and I'd go get him grapes and milk, oh, malted milks.
That's what we lived on for two weeks.
And then he was sick about a week, and I took care of him.
Then I became sick, and he took care of me.
And that's the only way we survived.
So you could, while one of you was sick, the other was well.
Right.
At least well enough to take care of the other.
Right.
And then you went, your father called you home because of a sickness in the family.
Yes, yes.
How would you describe the life in the dormitory as you remember it?
Well, my life was, I only had one occasion.
that I felt I was mistreated.
There was a Mexican from Laredo that, you know, when they walk in the mess hall, you all stand up until everyone's in, and they be seated.
And I had a terrific headache.
And I was leaning over my chair like this, you know, and he came up with his knee.
And he hit and kicked me with his knee much, much too hard.
And he hurt me.
And my brother-in-law saw it.
And he beat the stepping out of him.
That's the only time when I was mistreated.
Now, one time on Saturday night, I hadn't been there over, say, a couple of three weeks.
But I had some friends that told me on Saturday night, stick tight.
Just don't get out and run around.
You'll get in trouble.

They got me in one of the downstairs in the area, five of them, and they had those Sam Brown belts, and they made me stand on the table and hold my ankles, and they marched around me, and they hit me much too hard.
But if you turn loose your ankles, they start over.
So the second round, there was a window open over there, and I hit that window, and they never did get me again because on Saturday night, Trim Rigney,
was in 104, the fourth floor up there.
I mean, 401.
I'm sorry, I said it backwards.
And Saturday night, the minute it got dark, I was up there shining his boots, and they never touched me.
He took me back to my room and closed that door, and they never got me again.
So that was a regular Saturday night occurrence and you shined this other man's boots.

Yeah, and another thing that I didn't approve of at all, those inner courts, they would take toilet paper and wet it, especially a half a roll, and then they'd stand in this window up there and somebody going by down like on the second floor or the first floor, they'd hit them in the side of the head with that wet toilet paper and it hurt some boys real bad.
But overall, it was only your friends that hazed you, unless you'd get in one of those sessions like I was telling you about, and they had quite a few of those.
But anyone would be stupid to get in them.
You don't want to be that stupid.
Get with one of your buddies.
So the man whose boots you shined, Trig?
Trim Rigney.
Trim Rigney.
From Leonard, Texas, and he played shortstop for the Detroit Tigers.
Was he a senior then?
He was a senior then, yes.
And he was a, oh, he was a colonel, lieutenant colonel, very high-ranking officer.
So it was to the freshman's advantage then to have a,
An upperclassman.
If you don't have one, you're in trouble.
How was the food like in the mess hall?
Or what was it like, I should say?
It was real good.
Very good.
Plentiful.
And like there would be an upperclassman, probably a captain or something at the end of the table.
Then there'd be
There's 14 people at the table.
And this one had, the little fish was
They had these two inside.
There was an upperclassman at the end, an upperclassman at this corner, and probably an upperclassman here.
But the poor little old fish, here they were down in the middle.
And what's left, that's what they got.
But if you have a table with a good bunch of people, or you could wait and get seconds.
But in the morning, we'd have hotcakes.
And of course, they'd get the first ones, which would be
A little better, and then eggs, and they fed us good, ample.
You wouldn't complain about the food.
Other than the, if you can call it a privilege of hazing the freshmen, did the upperclassmen have additional privileges?
Did they have more freedom to move about than the fish did?
Oh, yeah, pretty much.
What sorts of things could they do?
Well, the freshmen, they couldn't go many places, you know what I mean?
They were restricted from, well, like the Y.
The Y would be full of upper freshmen.
There wouldn't be any room for the fish.
And all the pool tables would be busy with upperclassmen.
The fish wouldn't have a chance to play.
In other words, if you could get you an upperclassman, a friend, to get you in with them and let you play, fine.
Otherwise, you don't play.
I imagine there were not a whole lot of pool tables for a whole bunch of boys.
No, there wasn't.
They were down in the basement.
Why?
But we got along real good.
There's plenty to do.
What type of things did you do for recreation and entertainment?
Well, we talked mostly, and...
I had quite a few friends from out of the country, one especially from Lima, Peru.
And he was a very unusual boy.
And then I had a boy that his roommate was a boy by the name of Clegg from San Angelo.
And I spent some time with them.
In fact, we went to Lima, Peru.
This boy's father was a civil engineer, and he borrowed all the money from the United States in 1913 to build the railroads in Peru.
And when we got to Peru, the first thing I did, I went to the hotel and I got the assistant manager and told him that I would, if possible, I would like to contact this friend.
And he went to quite some
a bit of trouble and found out, yes, he is a civil engineer and worked for a railroad and lives in Lima.
And we can contact him.
And the next morning he came to me and said, I contacted him.
Two months ago, he died with a heart attack.
So this was sometime after you had known him as a student.
This was two or three years ago.
Two or three years ago.
And this was, I'm talking about 1917, 18.
Were there a goodly number of Latin American students on campus?
Many, many.
From all the countries.
In other words, the first time I ever saw soccer, they played, that's what they played, played soccer all the time.
Quiet athletes, good ones.
Did they just kind of have a pickup game of soccer, or did they have an organized?
No, no, no, no, no, just out on a football field or a drill field, and they'd just say like 15 or 20 of them, 25 would get together, and they'd have a deal.
It was not an intramural type?
No, no, no, no, there wasn't enough of them for that, what I mean is.
But you did have a lot of other intramural activities, I take it.
Oh, yes.
Did you participate in any?
Yes.
I played on the fish football team, and I weighed about 150 pounds, and I played the end.
The big old boy weighed about 210, came around, and
hit that knee, and I didn't play anymore.
I was too little.
Even then, you were too little.
Too small.
Today, if you're 150, they don't even think about you.
Do you remember any of the other things?
Did you ever have any movies on campus?
I don't remember.
I don't think so.
We were busy.
They kept us busy.
See, in 1917, we had extended drill.
We drilled.
You'd get up at 6 o'clock and go to Reveille, and you'd go to breakfast, and then you'd go to studies, and then when you're not in classes, you're out on that drill field.
When you go into extended drill,

uh drill but uh about how much of the time how much per day or per week would you say you drilled well we we had two hours every afternoon regular and then we had they called other times and back in 1918 while there was much worse but standing at attention there with all the
The boys were sick and everything, and they'd fall out just like flies.
Well, the man behind them was always supposed to take care of the man.
And then they had extra men behind, you know, like a squadron, to take care of a man in the rear ranks that fell out.
And out in that hot sun and everything, they fell out.
I mean, plenty of them.
This would be if you were lining up to march to meals or something?
Yeah, to march to meals and to drill.
And during drill, you had a lot of people.
You know, and you had to parade, you know, the inspection, you know.
And like the first company to go there, they might stand 20 minutes before they're inspected.
And standing out there in the hot sun, you know, in the afternoon is pretty rough, especially when you have the flu.
You had a daily inspection of the?
Well, I wouldn't say daily, but quite often, you know, because it, and the bad thing about then, your best buddies, they were leaving every day, you know, going into service.
In fact, it got down to where there was very few seniors on the, just very few.
Now, did some of them leave during the year of 1718, or was it mostly the 1819 when the
students were leaving?
Most of them, no, some of them left in 17, 18, but most of them, of course, early, well, they didn't come back to school in 18, and a lot of them left in 18.
So you had virtually a senior-less school there for a while.
Right, in 18.
Did you have any favorite instructors
During the time that you were there.
I had one of the nicest men, and he's an English teacher, and he was crippled.
One leg was, I'd say, an inch and a half shorter than the other.
His name was Biddle, and I think he helped me more.
He was like a father to me.
When I had a problem, I'd go to him, and he always listened and was real sweet to me.
Any other ones that you were particularly fond of?
Yes, because I can't call too many names.
But we had retired army officers, you know, as watchmen, you know.
And we had to walk a post, you know, with a gun and everything.
And they assigned you your position, you know, and took care of it and everything.
But what did we call them?
I'm trying to think.
But anyhow, they had retired, like, colonels and...
These were people who worked out of the commandant's office?
Yes.
You say you walked a post.
Did you walk a post just in the dormitory, or did you walk posts outside, too?
No, I never... Just in the dormitory.
And the retired military people who assigned you your posts...
Did they do anything in the way of instructing you to in military science?
Oh, yes, yes.
They told you how to go down and turn and how often to go around.
Yes, they taught you how to handle your gun to start with.
I gather the gun you carried on when you were on...
post was not loaded?
Oh, no, no, no.
Did you ever have occasion to fire your gun?
I mean, did you ever go to target practice or anything of that nature?
No.
Just marching, drilling?
No, I don't think I ever had a shell the whole time I was there.
I didn't want one.
Never had occasion to shoot the light out over Old Main, over the Main building?
No.
Was that a practice while you were there?
No.
There was a period when it was a very popular thing to do.
When I was there, they better not.
They were pretty rough on us.
They were strict.
They shoot out what they call Prexy's Moon, the light on top of what was then the new main building.
Not in our time.
Not in your time, no.
I suppose that was later when they had more students and less opportunity to control them completely.
We worked hard.
We were busy all the time.
There wasn't a lot of foolishness going on.
